const faqs = [
  { q: "How many words can an African Grey learn?",
    a: "Most well-socialised African Greys settle into a working vocabulary of a few dozen to a couple of hundred words and phrases, and the keenest reach several hundred — a documented few pass 1,000. More telling than the count is that Greys use words contextually, not as random mimicry, so even a 40-word bird can feel like it's holding a conversation." },
  { q: "Do African Greys really talk, or just mimic sounds?",
    a: "They genuinely talk in the sense that matters: they attach words to situations. An African Grey says 'hello' when someone arrives, asks 'want up?' to be picked up, and names objects it wants. Whether that is 'understanding' in the human sense is still debated, but Greys use speech as communication far more than any other parrot — which is why they're ranked the #1 talking species." },
  { q: "When do African Grey parrots start talking?",
    a: "Usually between 12 and 18 months, though some start as early as 9–10 months and others not until two years. Timneh African Greys often begin a few months earlier than Congos. The first 'word' is almost always a phrase tied to a repeated moment — a morning greeting, the bird's name, or 'hello' at the door." },
  { q: "Can a timid or shy African Grey still talk?",
    a: "Yes. A timid young Grey is usually a bird that hasn't settled yet, not a bird that will never talk. Once it trusts the room and the people in it, the talking almost always comes. Staring, pressure and a chaotic environment slow it down; calm routine, consistent phrases and patience speed it up." },
  { q: "Can African Greys say multiple-syllable words and whole phrases?",
    a: "They can. Greys move from single words to multi-syllable words, then to phrases and short sentences, typically across years two to five. Many string several words into a contextual phrase ('night night, see you tomorrow') and reproduce household sounds with eerie accuracy — the microwave beep, the phone, even another pet's name." },
  { q: "Do African Greys talk more at certain times of day?",
    a: "Often, yes. Like wild flocks calling at first and last light, many companion Greys have their chattiest spells at dawn and again in the early evening — a 'before-bed' wind-down where the bird runs through its favourite words. It's normal, it's a good sign of a content bird, and covering the cage settles it for the night." },
  { q: "Congo vs Timneh — which African Grey talks better?",
    a: "Both talk beautifully. Congos tend toward clearer, more human-sounding pronunciation and a slightly larger ultimate vocabulary; Timnehs usually start earlier and adapt faster to a new home. The gap is real but modest — a well-socialised bird of either subspecies out-talks a neglected one of the other every time. Socialisation matters far more than subspecies." },
  { q: "Are male or female African Greys better talkers?",
    a: "Neither — talking ability is not reliably tied to sex in African Greys. Both males and females can become outstanding talkers, and the famous research bird Alex was male only by coincidence. What actually predicts a strong talker is early socialisation and daily human conversation, not whether the bird is a hen or a cock. That's also why we DNA-sex every chick for the buyer's information, never as a talking promise — choose a Grey on temperament and how it was raised, not its sex." },
  { q: "Will my African Grey definitely talk?",
    a: "We never guarantee it, and you should be wary of any breeder who does. Talking depends on genetics, socialisation and — most of all — daily human interaction in the bird's home. We raise every chick with constant speech to give it the best possible odds, but talking is a relationship you build, not a feature you buy." },
];

