            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- 6. How do they actually talk? -->
        <h2 id="how" class={h2}>How Do African Greys Actually Talk — Mimicry or Real Understanding?</h2>
        <p class={p}>Here's the question every buyer is really asking: when an African Grey "talks," is anyone home? The honest answer is that Greys do something no other parrot reliably does — they tie words to situations. Most talking birds repeat sounds; a Grey says "hello" when you walk in, asks "want up?" to be lifted, and names the treat it's hoping for. That's the difference between a recording and a conversation.</p>

        <figure class="my-6">
          <img src="/congo-african-grey-talking-ability.webp" srcset="/congo-african-grey-talking-ability-500.webp 500w, /congo-african-grey-talking-ability-760.webp 760w, /congo-african-grey-talking-ability.webp 1100w" sizes="(min-width: 768px) 700px, 92vw" width="1100" height="600" alt="A Congo African Grey mid-vocalisation, illustrating how African Greys use words in context rather than simple mimicry" title="How African Greys talk — contextual speech | C.A.Gs" class="w-full rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
          <span class={figc}>African Greys don't just copy sounds — they tie words to the moment in front of them.</span>
        </figure>

        <h3 class={h3}>Is It Contextual Speech or Just Copying Sounds?</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>What Contextual Speech Looks Like Day to Day</h4>
        <p class={p}>Contextual speech is the whole point of an African Grey. The bird isn't running a tape — it's matching a learned phrase to the moment in front of it. Once you live with one you stop noticing the vocabulary count and start noticing the timing: the goodbye as you pick up your keys, the "night night" when the lights dim, the wolf-whistle aimed squarely at the dog.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Phrases our birds tie to a moment</h5>
        <p class={p}>In our home aviary the chicks pick up our routine before they pick up rare words — a morning greeting, "step up," the call we use at feeding. Those context phrases come first precisely because they're anchored to something that happens the same way every day, which is exactly how a Grey learns best.</p>
        <h6 class={h6} style="color:#b04228">Breeder note: why we don't call it "a parrot trick"</h6>
        <p class={p}>We're careful never to sell talking as a circus act, because framing it that way sets owners up to "drill" their bird and get nowhere. Treat it as communication — talk <em>to</em> the bird, narrate your day, respond when it speaks — and the vocabulary takes care of itself.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>What Did the Alex Studies Actually Prove?</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>What Dr. Pepperberg Documented Over 30 Years</h4>
        <p class={p}>The reason "African Grey understanding" is taken seriously at all traces to one bird. From 1977 to 2007, <a href="https://alexfoundation.org/" class={lnk} style="color:#b04228" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Dr. Irene Pepperberg studied a Congo African Grey named Alex</a> for three decades, and the findings reshaped how scientists think about animal cognition.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Objects, colours, shapes and the concept of "none"</h5>
        <p class={p}>Alex could identify around 50 objects, seven colours and five shapes, answer "how many?" up to six, grasp "same" and "different," and — remarkably — use the concept of "none." He requested items by name rather than just responding to cues. Whether every Grey shares that capacity or Alex was exceptional is still open, but it moved the conversation from "can parrots mimic?" to "what can a Grey actually understand?"</p>

        <figure class="my-6">
          <img src="/african-grey-parrot-learning-cognition.webp" srcset="/african-grey-parrot-learning-cognition-500.webp 500w, /african-grey-parrot-learning-cognition-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-parrot-learning-cognition.webp 1000w" sizes="(min-width: 768px) 700px, 92vw" width="1000" height="700" alt="A Congo African Grey parrot examining letter shapes, illustrating the cognition and contextual learning Dr. Pepperberg documented in Alex" title="African Grey cognition and learning — the Alex studies | C.A.Gs" class="w-full rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
          <span class={figc}>Greys don't just copy — Alex's work showed real cognition: grasping concepts, not running a tape.</span>
        </figure>

        <h6 class={h6} style="color:#b04228">Citation: The Alex Foundation</h6>
        <p class={p}>The full body of work lives at the Alex Foundation, and the species background at the <a href="https://parrots.org/encyclopedia/grey-parrot/" class={lnk} style="color:#b04228" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">World Parrot Trust's grey parrot profile ↗</a>. We point new owners to both, because the more you understand the mind you're bringing home, the better a talker you'll raise.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>How Does an African Grey Compare to Other Talking Parrots?</h3>
        <p class={p}>Set against a typical companion parrot, the gap isn't subtle. Most parrots mimic a handful of sounds; an African Grey builds a real vocabulary and — uniquely — uses it in context. Here's how the Grey stacks up against the average talking parrot.</p>
        <div class="-mx-4 sm:mx-0 my-4">
          <CompareTableE
            showHeader={false}
            showCtas={false}
