        <div class="cag-seam" aria-hidden="true"><span class="cag-seam__line"></span><img src="/cag-footer-logo.webp" alt="" width="200" height="66" loading="lazy" /><span class="cag-seam__line"></span></div>

        <!-- 7. Timeline -->
        <h2 id="timeline" class={h2}>When Do African Greys Start Talking? The Month-by-Month Timeline</h2>
        <p class={p}>The single most common disappointment we hear is "my Grey isn't talking yet" — almost always from an owner whose bird is doing exactly what it should for its age. Talking is a multi-year arc, not a switch. Here's the realistic timeline, the same one we walk every family through before a chick goes home.</p>

        <figure class="my-6">
          <img src="/african-grey-talking-development-milestones-infographic.webp" srcset="/african-grey-talking-development-milestones-infographic-500.webp 500w, /african-grey-talking-development-milestones-infographic.webp 900w" sizes="(min-width: 768px) 448px, 92vw" width="900" height="1612" alt="African Grey parrot speech development milestones infographic, from experimental sounds at 0 to 6 months to a 200 to 1,000-plus word vocabulary at 5 years and beyond" title="African Grey talking development milestones (0–6 months to 5+ years) | C.A.Gs" class="w-full max-w-md mx-auto rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
          <span class={figc}>African Grey speech milestones at a glance — read the month-by-month version below.</span>
        </figure>

        <div class="tl-spine">
          {timeline.map((t, i) => (
            <div class="tl-step">
              <span class="tl-dot">{i + 1}</span>
              <span class="tl-age">{t.age}</span>
              <p class="tl-head">{t.head}</p>
              <p class="text-stone-700 leading-relaxed text-[15px] mb-0">{t.text}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>

        <h3 class={h3}>What Should You Expect in the First Year?</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>From Babble to First Words (0–12 Months)</h4>
        <p class={p}>The first year is groundwork, not performance. Expect clicks, whistles and babble that slowly sharpen into a first recognisable word somewhere around the end of it. Pushing a six-month-old to "say hello" does nothing; talking to it constantly does everything.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Why the first "word" is usually a context phrase</h5>
        <p class={p}>That first word is rarely a random one you drilled — it's the phrase your bird hears in the same situation every day. Greys learn language the way toddlers do, by attaching sound to meaning, so the goodbye you say a thousand times beats the flashcard word you said ten times.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>How Does Vocabulary Grow From Year One to Five?</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>The 1–5 Year Expansion Curve</h4>
        <p class={p}>Years one through five are where a Grey earns its reputation. Vocabulary climbs from a handful of words to dozens, pronunciation clears up, and single words knit into phrases and short sentences. Most birds find their personality as talkers in this window — the jokers, the mimics, the quiet ones with three perfect words.</p>

        <div class="cag-seam" aria-hidden="true"><span class="cag-seam__line"></span><img src="/cag-footer-logo.webp" alt="" width="200" height="66" loading="lazy" /><span class="cag-seam__line"></span></div>

        <!-- 8. How many words -->
        <h2 id="words" class={h2}>How Many Words Can an African Grey Learn?</h2>
        <p class={p}>This is the number everyone wants, so here it is straight: a typical well-socialised African Grey settles into a working vocabulary of a few dozen to a couple of hundred words and phrases. The keenest reach several hundred, and a documented few have passed a thousand. But the count is the least interesting thing about it — a 40-word Grey that uses every word in context feels far more like a companion than a 200-word bird rattling off sounds.</p>

        <figure class="my-6">
          <img src="/african-grey-among-best-talking-birds.webp" srcset="/african-grey-among-best-talking-birds-500.webp 500w, /african-grey-among-best-talking-birds.webp 831w" sizes="(min-width: 768px) 360px, 70vw" width="831" height="1050" alt="A Congo African Grey, ranked the number-one talking bird, beside the realistic 200 to 1,000-plus word vocabulary range" title="How many words an African Grey can learn | C.A.Gs" class="w-full max-w-sm mx-auto rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
          <span class={figc}>Vocabulary can climb into the hundreds — but a Grey using 40 words in context beats one parroting 200.</span>
        </figure>

        <h3 class={h3}>Can African Greys Say Multiple-Syllable Words and Whole Phrases?</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>Single Words vs Phrases vs Sentences</h4>
        <p class={p}>Yes — and the progression is part of the fun. Greys move from single words to multi-syllable words, then to phrases, then to short sentences, usually across years two to five. Plenty of birds will string several words into a context-correct line ("night night, see you tomorrow") and reproduce household sounds with unnerving accuracy: the microwave, the phone, the smoke-alarm chirp you wish you'd never let them hear.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Realistic vocabulary ranges (200–1,000+)</h5>
        <p class={p}>Treat 200–1,000+ words as the ceiling of what's possible, not a target you're failing to hit. Most companion Greys land comfortably below it and are wonderful talkers anyway. Vocabulary tracks the conversation in the home far more than the genes — a Grey only ever learns the words it actually hears, said with meaning.</p>
        <h6 class={h6} style="color:#b04228">Citation: documented record-holders</h6>
        <p class={p}>The famous high counts — Alex's working set, and pet Greys credited with vocabularies in the hundreds — come from birds in language-rich homes with owners who narrated everything. They show the ceiling. Your bird's real number will be set at your kitchen table, not by its hatch certificate.</p>

        <div class="cag-seam" aria-hidden="true"><span class="cag-seam__line"></span><img src="/cag-footer-logo.webp" alt="" width="200" height="66" loading="lazy" /><span class="cag-seam__line"></span></div>

        <!-- 9. Do all talk / timid -->
        <h2 id="all" class={h2}>Do All African Greys Talk — and Can a Timid One?</h2>
        <p class={p}>No, not every African Grey becomes a talker — and any breeder who tells you otherwise is selling, not breeding. Greys have the highest talking <em>potential</em> of any parrot, but potential isn't a promise. The good news for nervous buyers: most birds that "don't talk" are birds that haven't been given the right conditions, not birds that can't.</p>

        <figure class="my-6">
          <img src="/african-grey-parrot-saying-hello.webp" srcset="/african-grey-parrot-saying-hello-500.webp 500w, /african-grey-parrot-saying-hello.webp 800w" sizes="(min-width: 768px) 700px, 92vw" width="800" height="600" alt="A hand-raised African Grey parrot mid-greeting, the kind of contextual hello even a once-timid Grey settles into" title="Do all African Greys talk — even timid ones | C.A.Gs" class="w-full rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
          <span class={figc}>Most "quiet" Greys are simply unsettled — once they trust the room, the hellos arrive.</span>
        </figure>

        <h3 class={h3}>Why Don't Some African Greys Talk?</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>Genetics, Socialisation and Personality</h4>
        <p class={p}>Three things decide it: a little genetics, a lot of early socialisation, and the bird's own personality. A Grey that spent its first year with minimal human contact almost always ends up with a smaller vocabulary, no matter how chatty its family becomes later. Some birds are simply quieter characters — brilliant, bonded, and content to whistle rather than recite.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>The first-year socialisation window</h5>
        <p class={p}>The first twelve months matter more than any other period. Birds raised with constant, gentle human interaction in that window have consistently better talking outcomes — which is the entire reason we hand-raise every chick in the house rather than in a barn, talking to them from weaning. You can't easily buy that back later.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>Can a Shy or Timid African Grey Still Become a Talker?</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>How a Quiet Bird Finds Its Voice</h4>
        <p class={p}>Almost always, yes. A timid young Grey is usually a bird that hasn't settled yet — new home, new people, everything unfamiliar — not a bird that will stay silent for life. Greys are <strong>neophobic</strong>; they distrust the new until it becomes routine. Give a shy bird a calm room, a predictable rhythm, and no pressure, and the talking tends to arrive once the trust does.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>What changes when a timid bird settles</h5>
        <p class={p}>The tell is usually private practice first: you'll catch a quiet Grey muttering its words to itself, alone, weeks before it ever performs for the room. That's the breakthrough. Staring at it, demanding "say hello," or a chaotic household all push it back into its shell; patience and a normal, talkative home draw it out.</p>
        <h6 class={h6} style="color:#b04228">Breeder note: our shy chicks still talk</h6>
        <p class={p}>We raise the occasional reserved chick, and we tell those families the truth — go slower, expect a longer runway — but in our experience the quiet ones get there. A timid bird isn't a non-talker. It's a talker on a longer timeline.</p>

        <Callout variant="tip" title="The fastest way to a talking Grey">
          <p>Stop trying to teach it. Just talk <em>to</em> it — narrate your morning, greet it the same way every day, answer when it speaks. Live, contextual conversation from someone the bird trusts beats every recording, app and flashcard ever made.</p>
        </Callout>

        <div class="cag-seam" aria-hidden="true"><span class="cag-seam__line"></span><img src="/cag-footer-logo.webp" alt="" width="200" height="66" loading="lazy" /><span class="cag-seam__line"></span></div>

        <!-- 10. Congo vs Timneh -->
        <h2 id="vs" class={h2}>Congo vs Timneh: Which African Grey Talks Better?</h2>
        <p class={p}>Both subspecies talk beautifully, and the rivalry is more fun than it is decisive. If you forced us to generalise: Congos tend toward clearer, more human-sounding pronunciation and a slightly larger ultimate vocabulary, while Timnehs usually start earlier and settle into a new home faster. The gap is real but modest.</p>

        <figure class="my-6">
          <img src="/congo-african-grey-parrot-talking.webp" srcset="/congo-african-grey-parrot-talking-500.webp 500w, /congo-african-grey-parrot-talking.webp 900w" sizes="(min-width: 768px) 420px, 80vw" width="900" height="900" alt="A Congo African Grey parrot mid-word, showing the clearer, more human-sounding delivery Congos are known for versus Timnehs" title="Congo vs Timneh African Grey talking ability | C.A.Gs" class="w-full max-w-md mx-auto rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
          <span class={figc}>Congos lean clearer, Timnehs start earlier — but socialisation outweighs subspecies every time.</span>
        </figure>

        <ComparisonTable columns={talkerCols} rows={talkerRows} verdict="Pick the bird, not the subspecies — a well-socialised Grey of either kind out-talks a neglected one of the other, every time." />

        <h3 class={h3}>How Do the Two Subspecies Differ as Talkers?</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>Timing, Clarity and Voice Quality</h4>
        <p class={p}>Timnehs often say their first words a few months ahead of Congos and tend to roll with change more easily, so a Timneh may chatter sooner in a brand-new home. Congos catch up and frequently overtake on clarity — that uncanny, almost human delivery Greys are famous for is usually a Congo. Timneh voices are often described as a touch raspier or softer, which many owners adore.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Why socialisation beats subspecies every time</h5>
        <p class={p}>Whichever you choose, the variable that actually moves the needle is how the bird was raised and how much you talk to it. The difference between a well-socialised Congo and a well-socialised Timneh is small; the difference between either of those and an under-socialised bird is enormous. Choose the individual chick and the breeder, not the label.</p>
        <h6 class={h6} style="color:#b04228">Breeder note: our Congos vs our Timnehs</h6>
        <p class={p}>Across our own clutches the pattern mostly holds — our Timnehs like <a href="/available/" class={lnk} style="color:#b04228">Elad and Evie</a> tend to find their voices a little earlier, our Congos a little clearer — but we've raised exceptions to every rule. We match families to a bird's temperament first and its subspecies second.</p>

        <div class="cag-seam" aria-hidden="true"><span class="cag-seam__line"></span><img src="/cag-footer-logo.webp" alt="" width="200" height="66" loading="lazy" /><span class="cag-seam__line"></span></div>

        <!-- 11. What develops it -->
        <h2 id="develops" class={h2}>What Actually Develops an African Grey's Talking Ability?</h2>
        <p class={p}>If talking were just genetics, every Grey from talkative parents would be a chatterbox and they aren't. What reliably builds a talker is exposure — daily, contextual human speech from a bird that feels safe enough to join in. Almost everything that helps is free, and almost everything that's sold as a shortcut doesn't work.</p>

        <figure class="my-6">
          <img src="/woman-talking-to-african-grey-parrot.webp" srcset="/woman-talking-to-african-grey-parrot-500.webp 500w, /woman-talking-to-african-grey-parrot-760.webp 760w, /woman-talking-to-african-grey-parrot.webp 900w" sizes="(min-width: 768px) 700px, 92vw" width="900" height="601" alt="A woman talking face to face with her African Grey parrot, the daily contextual human speech that builds a confident talker" title="What develops an African Grey's talking ability | C.A.Gs" class="w-full rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
          <span class={figc}>The single biggest driver of a talking Grey: someone who talks to it, daily, like it's listening.</span>
        </figure>

        <h3 class={h3}>What Do We Do at the Aviary to Build It?</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>Daily Speech From Weaning</h4>
        <p class={p}>Our chicks grow up inside the conversation, not beside it. From weaning they hear us greet them the same way each morning, name their food, and chat through hand-feeding and cleaning — so by the time a bird goes home it already associates human speech with safety and routine. That head start is the whole point of buying a properly hand-raised Grey instead of a parent-reared or imported one.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>What helps versus what wastes your time</h5>
        <p class={p}><strong>Helps:</strong> talking to the bird directly, consistent context phrases, a busy room, responding when it vocalises, and patience. <strong>Wastes your time:</strong> recordings on a loop (Greys tune them out), word-drilling flashcards, leaving a talk-radio station on as a babysitter, and — worst of all — any kind of punishment for not talking, which only teaches the bird to stay quiet around you.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>When Do African Greys Talk Most During the Day?</h3>
        <h4 class={h4}>Dawn Greetings and the Before-Bed Chatter</h4>
        <p class={p}>Like wild flocks calling at first and last light, companion Greys often have two chatty peaks: a morning burst as the house wakes, and an early-evening wind-down before sleep. That "talks before bedtime" habit owners notice is completely normal — the bird is running through its favourite words as the day closes, and it's a sign of a settled, content Grey.</p>

        <figure class="my-6">
          <img src="/african-grey-parrot-talking-microphone.webp" srcset="/african-grey-parrot-talking-microphone-500.webp 500w, /african-grey-parrot-talking-microphone-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-parrot-talking-microphone.webp 1000w" sizes="(min-width: 768px) 700px, 92vw" width="1000" height="596" alt="An African Grey parrot vocalising toward a microphone, reproducing household words and sounds with uncanny accuracy" title="When African Greys talk most during the day | C.A.Gs" class="w-full rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" loading="lazy" />
          <span class={figc}>Greys run through their favourite words at dawn and dusk — and mimic the sounds of the house with eerie accuracy.</span>
        </figure>

        <h5 class={h5}>Why evenings get chatty</h5>
        <p class={p}>Evenings are when the household finally slows down and the bird has your attention, so it's prime talking time. It's also why a consistent bedtime and a cage cover matter — let the chatter run a while, then cover the cage for the 10–12 hours of dark, quiet sleep a Grey needs to stay even-tempered the next day.</p>
        <h6 class={h6} style="color:#b04228">Breeder note: Maxy's evening wind-down</h6>
        <p class={p}>Maxy, the Congo in the video at the top of this page, is at his most talkative in the evening — which is exactly when we filmed him. If your Grey saves its best material for dusk, that's not a quirk; that's a Grey being a Grey.</p>

        <MythFact
          myth="African Greys are guaranteed to talk, and playing recordings on a loop teaches them faster."
          fact="No bird is guaranteed to talk, and looped audio actually slows them down — Greys tune out recordings. They learn from live, contextual conversation with people they trust. There is no shortcut that replaces you." />

        <BreederNote>
          <p>The owners with the most talkative Greys aren't the ones who bought a "guaranteed talker" or the most expensive bird — they're the ones who simply <em>talk to their bird like it's listening</em>. It is. That's the whole secret, it's free, and no breeder can sell it to you in a box.</p>
        </BreederNote>

        <div class="cag-seam" aria-hidden="true"><span class="cag-seam__line"></span><img src="/cag-footer-logo.webp" alt="" width="200" height="66" loading="lazy" /><span class="cag-seam__line"></span></div>

        <!-- 12. Will my bird talk? (decision tree) -->
        <h2 id="will" class={h2}>Will MY African Grey Talk? A Quick Decision Guide</h2>
        <p class={p}>Talking is a relationship, not a spec sheet — so the honest answer to "will mine talk?" depends mostly on your home and your routine. Find your situation below for a realistic read on the odds.</p>
